##I'm not a virus, I'm hugging 50 strangers in the streets of Paris

Micro-signal Zairenjian11

Features, with a calm narrative against the cold | phoenix network produced in the human studio

The following article is from the Earth's youth map, the author of green

The alternative to being young

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Affected by the outbreak, several countries have issued policies restricting the entry of Chinese tourists. Overseas, people have become wary of coronavirus infection, and with it, fear of Asian Americans, reports of repeated discrimination and violence against Chinese, and even equating the virus with the Chinese.

Li Ling, a Chinese girl in France who has faced discrimination in her life, decided to take to the streets and invite strangers to hug her to fight against the racism of the coronavirus.

Here is Li Ling's account.

I'm at the Tuileries Garden with the sign

I am Li Ling, from Guangdong, at the end of 2017, I came to a French University to study project management graduate students, just finished their studies and internships, now in Paris to study French language ability.

"You see, I'm glad I didn't go back, " I joked to my family in Paris when the outbreak first started. In the next few days, it became an international public health crisis. Some people avoid Wuhan at home, while others avoid Chinese people wearing masks abroad. Europeans sometimes lose sight of the faces of China, Japan and South Korea, so they have evolved to avoid Asians.

Notre Dame de Paris under construction

Around January 22, I heard about the first cases of confirmed cases in foreign countries, and I spent the day in the office discussing with my colleagues how to write an email to calm them down because the company often takes business trips to central Europe. A few hours later, I got off work and went home on the RER line, the Paris inter-city express, only to encounter my first "viral discrimination" .

At the end of the workday, RER was relatively crowded. I found a seat by the window, opposite a man. I couldn't tell if he was from France or any other country. I didn't notice at first, but when I sat down and looked up, I saw that the man had wrapped a scarf around his nose and mouth.

And I thought to myself, "is this because I'm contagious? "? Oh, come on. I must be imagining things. At the end of the 20-minute journey, I got out of the car, but as I turned to leave, I caught a glimpse of the man pulling down his scarf and taking a deep breath. At that moment, I was a little angry, but also helpless, others will be afraid of is normal, after home I also with French roommate jokes, let him avoid me.

Metro Paris

Unexpectedly, two days in a row, I had a similar experience in the subway and bus.

The next day I took the subway out, the subway is very noisy, but I clearly heard someone whisper Chinoise (Chinese) voice, glanced at it, found that is a group of French teenagers whispering. I didn't want to argue with them, but as I got out of the car and walked past the children, an older boy turned his back on me and pushed his friend away from me, c 'EST UNE Chinoise! (a Chinese man) I was pushed out of the car by the crowd, full of anger or sadness, and had been waiting to go home to tell my friends.

The French friend listened to also very angry, said to me, why don't you scold back on the spot? In France, we have to take a swipe at people like that and teach them a lesson. I laughed and said the next time I would take a shot, I would go online and start a discussion on the Hashtag "Coronaracism. ".

The buses in Paris

That night, however, there were two confirmed cases in France, and I became so anxious that I asked my French roommate to accompany me the next day when I needed to take a bus. He asked me why, I said I was afraid of being discriminated against again, he said disapprovingly, if you had a virus, then I would have been infected by you, even if you were sick, you could still get VIP treatment in France, this virus is not absolutely fatal, as for those who have no brains, ignore them.

I was comforted, feel better, but half an hour later on the bus, I encountered a passenger automatic "give up seat" self "clear" ...

Paris Tower in winter rain

When the racial discrimination caused by coronavirus has become the topic of daily conversation with friends and colleagues, suffering from virus discrimination caused by the anxiety of the past. For the next few weeks, I didn't care if I was shunned, thinking it was them who were in trouble, not me.

What really bothered me, was the outpouring of news about the outbreak on facebook and twitter, the anger, the sadness, the resignation, and the fact that no one had ever tried to support the front line medical staff as much as they did now.

The anger and sadness that the small screen of my phone conveyed gave me a strong sense of anxiety and anxiety, and I was once afraid to open my Weibo and friends circle. Overseas Chinese also began to suffer more unfair discrimination, international students have been bullied more and more news, let me feel and sad.

The cards I make

I started thinking about what I could do. In fact, my life in France is very stressful, I can not like some people to go to the streets to buy masks sent back to the country, but do not want to just point fingers forwarding articles.

At the end of January, after I finished work and had a little emotional breakdown, I read a passage from Nitze's book Human, All Too Human: the first thought of the day -- call it a good start, the best way to do this is to wake up and think about whether today brings happiness to at least one person. If this idea can be used as a substitute for the religious practice of prayer, then everyone can benefit from this change.

I woke up the next day with an idea: how about I do a Free Hug in Paris.

I give hugs on the street in front of the Arc de Triomphe

"Are you crazy! " Was the first reaction of my French friends when they heard I was going to Free Hug on the streets of Paris. It wasn't until I finished the cardboard and showed them the real thing in the photo that they believed I was actually going to do it.

I've been working on this for four days. What was written on the cards was my own idea at first, and then my French friend gave me an idea. From the slightly funny beginning to the last sentence, "don't panic, I'm not a virus, " there is also a bit of French humor. I don't want to take it too seriously, but I want to do something fun and easy and thoughtful in a very tense and anxious environment.

Actually, this isn't my first Free Hug. In 2015, I launched a crowdfunding project called 100 Free Hugs, when I was traveling in South Korea for 11 days and challenged myself to collect 100 Hugs from strangers on an exotic street. So street Free Hug is a familiar road, but the difference is, now in a more tense environment. Living in Paris for more than two years, I probably understand that hugging is a close relationship between French people and their relatives and friends, and Parisians are relatively "cold" , so the challenge of hugging strangers is still there.

The weather in Paris in winter is mostly cold and rainy, but just this week when I decided to do Free Hug, Paris gave me a sunny day. On the morning of February 7, I was having a French class near new triumphal arch, La Défense, so I decided to start the hug at 2 p.m. in La Défense and head east to Triumphal Arch, the Champs Elysées, the tuileries and the Louvre.

At noon, the new Arc de Triomphe on the grand staircase sat a lot of lunch time in the sun, eat white-collar and students. When I got to my friend, who was a photographer, I started holding up a sign and coming down the stairs, laughing at the people on the steps, talking to my friends all the time to relieve my inner tension.

It's not the first time I've been Free Hug, but I'm still nervous, and I'd be embarrassed if I got rejected. I am not afraid of someone scold me, but worry about no one to ignore, indifference is the most sad.

Next to the great steps of the new Arc de Triomphe, I gave my first hug.

I stood holding the sign for a while before I received my first hug from a French boy who was sitting next to me while I waited for my friend on the steps. He looked at me and waved at me with a smile. I didn't realize it for a moment, so he got up and walked up to me and gave me a hug.

The Yellow Hoodie boy made a whole heart with his hands and me.

Gradually, several French girls came down the long flight of stairs and hugged me. Another group of teenagers, who looked like high school students, looked at me from a distance at first, and after a while, they lined up to give me a hug. One of the Yellow Hoodie boys do not want to hug, he compared the hands of half a heart, let my hand with him to form a complete heart, to express support, really cute. Feel the world or more good people, the heart has become a little easier.

Hug The children

I then turned to the Arc de Triomphe and the Champs Elysees, here is full of tourists, tourists still have a sense of distance, everyone in front of the attractions in their own photos, looked at me and the sign, did not pay attention to me.

I don't get a lot of hugs here, but there's a funny moment. On the Champs Elysees, a group of French high school students passed by, saw my sign and shouted "embrace" , then pushed a little boy to me, the little boy was stunned, asked me what this is, I said it is a hug, not afraid, I am not a virus, the boy didn't react, but he did lean towards me, so I hugged him and laughed.

At the Tuileries, I hugged an old man.

Frustrated at the Arc de Triomphe and the Champs Elysées, I dragged my friend to the TUILERIES, where the French go for walks in their spare time. As soon as I arrived at Tuileries, I met a French man with a Spanish accent and English accent. He saw my sign and came up to hug me and chat with us.

The man had been to China many times, and when he saw the J e Ne Suis Pas UN virus on my sign, he began to think, I am not a virus, china this is very difficult, I hope you get better soon, those who say you are a virus, ignore them, they have no brain. I was happy to hear that, because he was the first person since Free Hug this afternoon to stop and really talk to us, and finally be able to talk more about this topic with others.

At the TUILERIES, I hugged my gray-haired aunt.

After I said goodbye to him, I met a group of old friends, mostly French, and one of them pointed to my sign and joked to the other, look, there's a free hug, and he shook his head and said, no, no, no. I pointed to the sign and said, don't be afraid, I'm not a virus.

The smiling gray-haired aunt slapped the uncle and said, Oh, you guys go away, and then gave me a hug, and told me that this behavior of yours is too cute, ignore them, and began to pull me to talk enthusiastically about everyday life, the uncles were infected by her, finally, he gave me a big hug and told me to go for it.

Delta hugs a girl at the Tuileries Garden.

At the Tuileries Garden, I gave the most hugs. I was most impressed by a father who, after seeing me, half pushed his little girl in front of me. The little girl smiled but was very shy. After several encouraging glances from her father, she reached over and gave me a hug. I looked at the father hand holding his son, from the appearance may be autistic, it should be a very difficult family. Suddenly felt that this hug, the girl may need to muster a lot of courage, and her father would be willing to push her in front of a stranger, to achieve. I can not help whispering in her ear to her, you look good today, to continue to refuel Oh!

I hugged a girl on the champs-elysees.

Finally in the Louvre ready to end, met a well-dressed British gentleman. He and his friend saw my sign across the street and kept laughing and talking. When he crossed the street and looked at me, I opened my hand, he waved no, no, no, I did not expect to walk a few steps back. I asked why AH, he smiled and said I was afraid, I said what Ah, I am not a virus, he said I do not know Ah, while giving me a hug.

Before I left, I discussed with my friends that it would be nice to have 10 people willing to hug me today, but I didn't realize that there would be more than 50 people willing to hug me. Paris is not so cold as the French people say.

? ? Hugging a guy at the Tuileries Garden.

Because of the virus, we self-isolation wear masks, with a way to protect each other at a distance, but because of cultural differences, by people who do not understand the foreign people as Menghu. At present, there are very few people wearing masks on the streets of France. I have only met a few Asian faces wearing masks. The French public have a strong foundation of medical knowledge and health awareness. If they are sick, they will stay at home and not go out, people on the street wearing masks, to them, means that you are already sick, but you have to go out, which is potentially endangering the safety of others, creating panic.

I am still abroad, with a healthy me, in a safe environment, hope that through this small action, let everyone laugh, let everyone see some warm humanity in this chaotic and uneasy world, to calm the restless mind.

Hugs may seem simple, but they allow the person who accepts them to briefly unmask and feel warmth in that moment. Behind every strange hug is the trust of the human heart. There isn't much reason, just pure kindness and trust.

I hugged a boy on the champs-elysees.

In the process of giving hugs on the streets of Paris, I have seen a lot of people look at my sign and see something in their eyes, from curiosity, interest, hesitation to giving up. I believe that there is a powerful and tender force in the hearts of those who, in the brief moment of meeting and passing by, finally make up their minds to come to me, that can drive him to drop his guard and go to a stranger for a hug.

Just like one of the boys saw my sign from a distance and without hesitation walked up to me with his hands open and a smile on his face and said in a soft voice, "Why do you do this? " (Why do you do this?) I replied, "To make you happy and smile, I guess? Why do you hug me? " "I don't know! But it looks Nice! "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
When it was over, I posted the video to the facebook group and received some initial criticism. I was a bit of a coward at the time, and I was afraid I wouldn't be able to take it too well, so I pushed the message to shut it down. By the end of the day, I had the courage to open up the group and saw more than 30 comments on the Post, some questioning me, others defending me, and one Mexican who had experienced discrimination during the H1N1 flu era fighting for me. At that moment, I felt that it was okay to be scolded, at least everyone was already talking about it, and there would always be some people who began to understand.

I think there are warm people and narrow-minded people in every country. There is always discrimination, and it belongs to one voice in the world, but we can choose to fight it with another voice, and when others hear it, they will judge and act to change it.

By Li Ling
